label: 1870 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT FOREWORD  The following pages are alphabetical indices to be used in conjunction with the 1860, 1870, and 1880 censuses for the area which is now known as Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from these indices, it is well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This ‘knowledge will help you to deal with the complexities of the censuses.  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for 19th-century census enumerators. In an era when illiteracy was an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling of names. Five variations of O'Brien and four variations of Sullivan appear in the 1880 census alone. .  Writing can appear in tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near-sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, May not coincide with your version, as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, "sounds-like," and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire.  B. Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon. A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census-takers who took the job only for what they could  get out of it or because it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census schedules reflect this because the instructions which the census-takers received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a family by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. ' Sometimes’ families were not home when the census~taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times when young children in the family provided the "facts" for the census enumeration if no one else was at home.  Some persons moved frequently and appear more than once within the same census, and some census-takers padded the population. Apparently reimbursed in proportion to the number of families enumerated,

label: 1870 Lake County Census
text: they listed many families twice in different parts of their schedules, sometimes varying the information slightly.  C. Often incorrect data, which resulted in inconsistencies in the subsequent censuses, was given to the assistants and enumerators by members of the family. Inconsistent ages illustrate the problem best but places of birth and names also have some small tendency to change from one census to the next.  D. Too often the census schedules are. difficult to read, and there are many reasons for this. In addition to careless writing, unfamiliar abbreviations and the workings of time on poor quality inks are all familiar problems. There are additional problems in reading microfilmed’ copies of the censuses. On some the photography was poor -- under-exposure, over-exposure, etc. Others present special photography problems, such.  as the writing was faded and simply did not photograph well.  The author of these indices encountered all of the above-mentioned problems and more. Familiarity with certain names, knowing that the Henry A. W. Tabor in the 1870 census was really Horace A. W. Tabor, added greatly to the frustration of this project. It is hoped, however, that these indices will, in some small way,‘ help to alleviate your frustration in working with ane censuses.  Nancy Manly, Indexer Sherrill Warford, Typist Historical Research Cooperative  Extracted in part from: Researcher's Guide to American Genealogy

label: 1870 Lake County Census
text: ,  NOTE  “~  In 1870, Colorado was a Territory and Lake County covered a vast area which extended from the backbone of the Rocky Mountains to the Utah border.  The 1870 census for Lake County is divided into four sections for four population centers; namely, Centerville, Fairplay, Granite, and Oro City. Due to later restructuring of Colorado counties, Centerville and Granite are now in Chaffee County and Fairplay is in Park County. The site of Oro City remains in Lake County.  The mystery is: "What became of the population between the Rockies and Utah?”

text: IMPORTANT FOREWORD  The following pages are an alphabetical fndex to be used tn conjunction with the 1900 census for Lake County, Colorade, To derive the greatest benefit from this Index, It Is well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountesed fn comp! ling this ald. This knowledge will help you to deal with complexities of the census.  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for early 20th=-century census enumerators. In an era when [illiteracy was stil! an accepted way of IIfe, this Is not surprising. What Is surprising ts the occasionally creative, albelt erroneous, spelling of names,  Questionable spelling of last names Is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work, All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer In regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator except in those cases when other sources provide a more logical spelling. In these rare Instances, the accepted spelling appears In alphabetical order and the name as it appears in the census follows In parenthesis, It Is vitally Important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, “sounds=-like," forelgn and Americanized version, and even reverse placement of names, !.e,. James, Joseph Instead of Joseph, James, You may even wish to run through all names within an alphebetical category for the name you desire.  Writing can appear In tangled, Victorian flour!lshes; cramped, nearesighted scratches; or lovely, fiuld penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents Its own problems for deciphering the hidden message, Our version, copled as we saw It, may not coincide with your version, as you see It,  B. Incompleteness In a census Is not uncommon, A census can be Incomplete In spite of a conscientious census-taker, However, there have been census-takers who took the Job only for what they could  get out of It or because It was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not wel! quatified and did not satisfactorl ly fulfill thelr obligations, Many of the eensus schedules reflect  this because the Instructions which the census-takers rece! ved  (or should have recelved) were not fol lowed,  Some schedules IIst persons In a family by Initials only, A few schedules |ist no places of birth or age. Sometimes familtes were not home when the enumerator made his vistt and nelghbors were asked to give the Information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own  a ei

label: 1860 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT FOREWORD  The following pages are alphabetical indices to be used in conjunction with the 1860, 1870, and 1880 censuses for the area which is now known as Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from these indices, it is well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This ‘knowledge will help you to deal with the complexities of the censuses.  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for 19th-century census enumerators. In an era when illiteracy was an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling of names. Five variations of O'Brien and four variations of Sullivan appear in the 1880 census alone. .  Writing can appear in tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near-sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, May not coincide with your version, as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, "sounds-like," and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire.  B. Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon. A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census-takers who took the job only for what they could  get out of it or because it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census schedules reflect this because the instructions which the census-takers received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a family by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. ' Sometimes’ families were not home when the census~taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times when young children in the family provided the "facts" for the census enumeration if no one else was at home.  Some persons moved frequently and appear more than once within the same census, and some census-takers padded the population. label: 1880 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT FOREWORD  The following pages are alphabetical indices to be used in conjunction with the 1860, 1870, and 1880 censuses for the area which is now known as Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from these indices, it is well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This ‘knowledge will help you to deal with the complexities of the censuses.  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for 19th-century census enumerators. In an era when illiteracy was an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling of names. Five variations of O'Brien and four variations of Sullivan appear in the 1880 census alone. .  Writing can appear in tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near-sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, May not coincide with your version, as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, "sounds-like," and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire.  B. Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon. A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census-takers who took the job only for what they could  get out of it or because it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census schedules reflect this because the instructions which the census-takers received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a family by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. ' Sometimes’ families were not home when the census~taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times when young children in the family provided the "facts" for the census enumeration if no one else was at home.  Some persons moved frequently and appear more than once within the same census, and some census-takers padded the population. Apparently reimbursed in proportion to the number of families enumerated,

text: they listed many families twice in different parts of their schedules, sometimes varying the information slightly.  C. Often incorrect data, which resulted in inconsistencies in the subsequent censuses, was given to the assistants and enumerators by members of the family. Inconsistent ages illustrate the problem best but places of birth and names also have some small tendency to change from one census to the next.  D. Too often the census schedules are. difficult to read, and there are many reasons for this. In addition to careless writing, unfamiliar abbreviations and the workings of time on poor quality inks are all familiar problems. There are additional problems in reading microfilmed’ copies of the censuses. On some the photography was poor -- under-exposure, over-exposure, etc. Others present special photography problems, such.  as the writing was faded and simply did not photograph well.  The author of these indices encountered all of the above-mentioned problems and more. Familiarity with certain names, knowing that the Henry A. W. Tabor in the 1870 census was really Horace A. W. Tabor, added greatly to the frustration of this project. It is hoped, however, that these indices will, in some small way,‘ help to alleviate your frustration in working with ane censuses.  Nancy Manly, Indexer Sherrill Warford, Typist Historical Research Cooperative  Extracted in part from: Researcher's Guide to American Genealogy

label: 1860 Lake County Census
text: they listed many families twice in different parts of their schedules, sometimes varying the information slightly.  C. Often incorrect data, which resulted in inconsistencies in the subsequent censuses, was given to the assistants and enumerators by members of the family. Inconsistent ages illustrate the problem best but places of birth and names also have some small tendency to change from one census to the next.  D. Too often the census schedules are. difficult to read, and there are many reasons for this. In addition to careless writing, unfamiliar abbreviations and the workings of time on poor quality inks are all familiar problems. There are additional problems in reading microfilmed’ copies of the censuses. On some the photography was poor -- under-exposure, over-exposure, etc. Others present special photography problems, such.  as the writing was faded and simply did not photograph well.  The author of these indices encountered all of the above-mentioned problems and more. Familiarity with certain names, knowing that the Henry A. W. Tabor in the 1870 census was really Horace A. W. Tabor, added greatly to the frustration of this project. It is hoped, however, that these indices will, in some small way,‘ help to alleviate your frustration in working with ane censuses.  Nancy Manly, Indexer Sherrill Warford, Typist Historical Research Cooperative  Extracted in part from: Researcher's Guide to American Genealogy

label: 1860 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT NOTE  In 1860, the state of Colorado did not exist. It's area was encompassed by Kansas Territory. And, in 1860, Lake County did not exist, either. Arapahoe County, Kansas Territory, covered a vast portion of what is now Colorado, including the present Lake County.  For the purpose of this index, only that portion of Arapahoe County which relates to Lake County has been extracted, namely the California Gulch segment. The rush of gold-seekers into California Gulch began in April of 1860. The hundreds of names appearing here, which were enumerated during the summer of 1860, attest to the lure of the precious metal.

text: This project is dedicated to us because we finished what we set out to do.

label: 1910 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT FOREWORD  .The following pages are an alphabetical index to be used in _conjunction with the 1910 census for Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from this index, it is well that you,  the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This knowledge will help you to deal with the complexities of the census.  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for early 20th-century census enumerators. In an era  when illiteracy was still an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling of names.  Writing can appear in tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near= sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, may not coincide with your version, as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator except in those cases when other sources provide a more logical spelling. In these rare instances, the accepted spelling appears in alphabetical order and the name as it appears in the census follows in parenthesis. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, "sounds-like," foreign and Americanized versions, and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire.  B. Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon. A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census- takers who took the job only for what they could get out of it or because it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census schedules reflect this because the instructions which the enumerators received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a family by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. Sometimes families were not home when the census-taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times when young children in the family provided the "facts" for the census enumeration if no one else was at home.

label: 1910 Lake County Census
text: iC. Often incorrect data, which resulted in inconsistencies in the subsequent censuses, was given to the assistants and enumerators by members of the family. Inconsistent ages illustrate the problem best but places of birth and names also have some small tendency to change from one census to the next.  The author of this index encountered all of the above-mentioned  problems and more. It is hoped, however, that this aid will, in some small way, help to alleviate your frustration in working with the census.  Historical Research Cooperative  Extracted in part from: Researcher's Guide to American Genealogy

label: 1920 Lake County Census
text: The 1920 United States Census of Lake County, Colorado, consists of Enumeration Districts 72 through 85--a total of 17 precincts.  Transcription was made from the 1920 U. S. Census, T625, Roll 165.  Names appear as read by transcriber. No attempt was made to adjust spelling to known correct spelling.

label: 1920 Lake County Census
text: GENERAL INFORMATION  Enumeration Districts In most cases, the Enumeration Districts (ED) of Lake County, Colorado Federal Census represent a specific precinct. However,  some contain more than one precinct.  Precincts represented by each ED are as follows:  ED 72, Pct. 1 ED 79, Pct. 8  ED 73, Pct. 2 ED 80, Pct. 9  ED 74, Pct. 3 ED 81, Pcts. 10, 12, 13 ED 75, Pct. 4 ED 82, Pct. 11  ED 76, Pct. 5 ED 83, Pct. 14, 15  ED 77, Pct. 6 ED 84, Pct. 16  ED 78, Pct. 7 Ed 85, Pct. 17  Each ED has numbered sheets. The numbers appear in the upper right-hand corner of each sheet. Only the ED number and the Sheet Number are used in this index.     Supervisor District__ Sheet No.  Enumeration District “0c _ 2e ad  2 Ward of City     There are often other numbers and comments written in by the census taker.  Each census also has numbered lines. Usually the "A" pages run  from 1-50; the "B" pages run from 51-100. However, due to census taker error, the "A" and "B" numbering may be reversed.  Reading the All-Name Index  The all-name index contains the following (example):  ABBOTT, BLANCH X “7 S a name age sex sheet No. line No.  To find a name in the original census film, follow these steps:  1) Roll the film to the ED number needed  2) Find the correct "A" or "B" page  3) Find the name on the numbered line of the oa or soe page.

label: 1930 Lake County Census
text: IMPORTANT FORWARD  The following pages are an alphabetical index to be used in  conjunction with the 1930 census for Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from this index, it is well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This knowledge will help you to deal with the complexities of the census.  A.  Aptitude for spelling and writing does not appear to have been prerequisites for early 20"-century census enumerators. In an era when illiteracy was still an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling of names.  Writing can appear tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near- sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship, which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, may not coincide with your version, as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All names have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator except in those cases when other sources provide a more logical spelling. In these rare instances, the accepted spelling appears in alphabetical order and the name as it appears in the census follows in parenthesis. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, “sounds-like,” foreign and Americanized versions, and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire.  Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon. A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census-takers who took the job only for what they could get out of it or because it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census

label: 1930 Lake County Census
text: schedules reflect this because instructions that the enumerators received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a family by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. Sometimes families were not home when the census-taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant were personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times when young children in the family provided the “facts” for the census enumeration if no one else was at home.  C. | Members of the family gave often-incorrect data, which resulted in inconsistencies in the subsequent censuses, to the assistants and enumerators. Inconsistent ages illustrate the problem best but places of birth and names also have some small tendency to change from one census to the next.  The author of this index encountered all of the above-mentioned problems and more. It is hoped, however, that this aid will, in some small way, help to alleviate your frustration in working with the census.  Extracted in part from: Researcher’s Guide to American Genealogy

text: IMPORTANT  FOREWORD  The following pages are an alphabetical -index to be used in conjunction with the 1885 census for Lake County, Colorado. To derive the greatest benefit from this index, it its well that you, the researcher, understand the difficulties encountered in compiling this aid. This knowledge will ‘help you to deal . with the complexities of the census,  A. Aptitude for spelling and writing does not now appear to have been prerequisites for 19th=-century census enumerators. In an era when illiteracy was an accepted way of life, this is not surprising. What is surprising is the. occasionally creative, albeit erroneous, spelling. of names.  Writing can appear in tangled, Victorian flourishes; cramped, near-sighted scratches; or lovely, fluid penmanship which has faded to near nothingness. Every style presents its own problems for deciphering the hidden message. Our version, copied as we saw it, may not coincide with your eae as you see it.  Questionable spelling of last names is considered to be one of the most prominent hazards within this work. All mames have been recorded as interpreted by the Indexer in regards to careless writing, and as spelled by the enumerator except in those cases when other sources provide a more logical spelling. In these rare instances, the accepted spelling appears in alphabetical order and the name as it appears in the census follows in parenthesis. It is vitally important, therefore, that you search for every possible spelling variation, "sounds like,"' and even reverse placement of names, i.e. James, Joseph instead of Joseph, James. You may even wish to run through all names within an alphabetical category for the name you desire,  B. Incompleteness in a census is not uncommon, A census can be incomplete in spite of a conscientious census-taker. However, there have been census—takers who took the job only for what they could get out of it or hecause it was assigned to them by legislative act. Many of these persons were not well qualified and did not satisfactorily fulfill their obligations. Many of the census schedules reflect this because the instructions which the census-takers received (or should have received) were not followed.  Some schedules list persons in a famiiy by initials only. A few schedules list no places of birth or age. Sometimes families were not home when the census=taker made his visit and neighbors were asked to give the information, or if the assistant was personally acquainted with the family he would complete the schedules to the best of his own knowledge. There were also times

The author of these indices encountered all of the above-mentioned problems and more, It is hoped, however, that this: index will, in some small way, help to aes your frustration in ee with~ the census,  Nancy Manly, Indexer Sherrill Warferd, Typist Historical Research Cooperative  Extracted in part from: - ‘ - Researcher's | eniaey to American Ge logy
